450","1295–1360":"1295–1360","1335–1380":"1335–1380","about 1380":"about 1380","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1414":"1414","1424":"1424","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1377":"1377","about 1424":"about 1424","about 1414":"about 1414","1375":"1375","about 1355":"about 1355","about 1375":"about 1375","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Clayton, Lancashire":"Clayton Le Woods, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Whittle le Woods, Lancashire, England":"Whittle le Woods, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crook","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","topographic name from Old Norse <i>krókr</i> ‘nook or bend’ denoting someone who lived by a bend in a river or road. In some instances the surname may have arisen as a habitational name from any of the places called Crook in Cumberland and Durham, or Crooke in Lancashire, all of which are derived from this word.","topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) barrow or mound’ from Brittonic <i>crüg</i>. In some instances this may have arisen as a habitational name from either Crook in Combe Raleigh or perhaps Crooke in North Tawton (both Devon), which are derived from this word."],"variants":[{"name":"Crooker","meanings":["English: from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>crok</i> ‘bend’ (Old Norse <i>krókr</i> ‘hook, bend’), probably applied as a topographic name for someone who lived at a bend; compare   Crook  ."]},{"name":"Croxton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Leicestershire, Norfolk, and Staffordshire named Croxton, from the Old Norse personal name <i>Krókr</i> (see   Crook   3) or an Old English word <i>crōc</i> ‘nook’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’."]},{"name":"Crooke","meanings":["English: variant of   Crook  ."]},{"name":"Crooks","meanings":["habitational name from Crookes in Sheffield (Yorkshire), named with Old Norse <i>krókr</i> ‘hook, bend’.","variant of   Crook  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English:"]},{"name":"Croak","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Crook  .","Americanized form of German   Krock   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Croke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Brendan, Fergus, Kieran.","English (Lancashire) and Irish (Cork): variant of   Crook  . According to Woulfe, the English name was taken to Ireland in the 13th century; the <i>Croke</i> family settled in Kilkenny, Tipperary, and Cork, whilst   Crooke   represents a later immigration and is more widespread.","Americanized form of Polish   Krok   and German   Krock   or some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Crook was born about 1375, in Clayton, Lancashire, England, his father, Richard Croc, was 82 and his mother, Mrs. Clemency Croc, w